Kafkaesque describes a disorientingly complex, bizarre, or nightmarish situation. 

It primarily refers to experiences with oppressive, illogical, or nonsensical bureaucratic systems where an individual feels powerless, 

isolated, and unable to understand the rules or escape the overwhelming red tape.

The term originates from the German-language Czech author Franz Kafka (1883–1924), 

whose surreal fiction frequently explored the alienation and helplessness of modern individuals facing blind, impersonal authority.

A classic example is his novel The Trial, where the protagonist is arrested and tried by a labyrinthine, 

faceless legal system for a crime that is never revealed.While the word is often casually used to mean simple bureaucratic frustration,

true Kafkaesque scenarios involve a profound loss of control and an inescapable sense of the absurd.
